{{Redirect2|Ca.|Cca.|other uses of "Ca"|CA (disambiguation){{!}}CA|other uses of "Cca"|CCA (disambiguation){{!}}CCA}}

'''Circa''' ({{ety|la||around, about}}) - frequently abbreviated '''c.''', '''ca.''', or '''ca''' (and less frequently '''circ.''' or '''cca.''') – signifies "approximately" in several European languages (and as a [[loanword]] in English), usually in reference to a date.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/circa |title=circa |publisher=[[Dictionary.com]] |access-date=16 July 2010}}</ref> ''Circa'' is widely used in historical writing when the dates of events are not accurately known.

When used in date ranges, ''circa'' is applied before each approximate date, while dates without ''circa'' immediately preceding them are generally assumed to be known with certainty.
Example: [[George Washington]] years are:
* 1732–1799 or 1732–99: Both years are known precisely.
* {{circa|lk=no|1732}} – 1799: Only the end year is known accurately; the start year is approximate.
* 1732 – {{circa|lk=no|1799}}: Only the start year is known accurately; the end year is approximate.
* {{circa|lk=no|1732|1799}}: Both years are approximate.

