[[Image:Institut Lumière Lyon.jpg|thumb|The Instiut Lumière in Lyon]]
The '''Institut Lumière''' ({{IPA-fr|ɛ̃s.ti.ty ly.mjɛːʁ|pron}}; "Lumière Institute") is a French organisation, based in [[Lyon]], for the promotion and preservation of aspects of French [[film]] making. The Institut Lumière is a museum that honours the contribution to filmmaking by [[Auguste and Louis Lumière]] - inventors of the [[cinématographe]] and fathers of the [[film|cinema]].
It was founded in 1982 by Bernard Chardère and Maurice Trarieux-Lumière, the grandson of Louis Lumière.<ref name="Mandelbaum2017">{{cite news|last1=Mandelbaum|first1=Jacques|title=« Lumière !, l’aventure commence » : les toutes premières fois du cinéma|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/cinema/article/2017/01/24/lumiere-l-aventure-commence-les-toutes-premieres-fois-du-cinema_5068025_3476.html|accessdate=10 February 2017|work=[[Le Monde]]|date=24 January 2017|language=FR}}</ref> [[Bertrand Tavernier]] is its president and [[Thierry Frémaux]] is its director. The museum is located within the house of the Lumière family, in the [[Monplaisir (Lyon)|Monplaisir]] quarter of Lyon. The film ''[[La Sortie de l'usine Lumière à Lyon]]'', one of the earliest motion pictures ever made, was shot in the immediate vicinity of the Institut.
The rehabilitation of the former Lumière factories was confided to the architect Pierre Colboc and the Chief architect of historic monuments Didier Repellin, associated with the agency [[Ducks Scéno|dUCKS Scéno]] for the scenography of the cinema and the outer spaces.
