'''Iris Habib Elmasry''' (إيريس حبيب المصري) was a prominent [[Copt]]ic [[Coptic history|Historian]] (1910–1994).<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=http://www.wataninet.com/article_en.asp?ArticleID=14312|title=Watani on Iris Habib el-Masri}}</ref>
==Biography== '''Iris Habib Elmasry''' was born into a Coptic family in 1910. Her family name ''Elmasry'' in the [[Arabic language]] means [[Egyptians|The Egyptian]].{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}
Her father Habib Elmasry was the secretary of the [[General Congregation Council]] of the [[Coptic Orthodox Church]]. She had two brothers; Amin, who was a prominent surgeon, and died in the 1960s, and Sami who was director of the Egyptian State Bureau for Tourism in London, and three sisters; Eva, who helped Iris in her work,<ref name="Copts">{{cite web|url=http://ukmidcopts.org/kotob/STRCOPT1.pdf|title=The story of the Copts By Iris habib Elmasry page 7|format=PDF}}</ref> Soraya, an avid pianist, and Dora, who was married to Dr Aziz El Masry<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.copticmedical.com/Masry.htm|title=Coptic Medical society on Dr Aziz Elmasry|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070406100819/http://www.copticmedical.com/Masry.htm|archivedate=2007-04-06|df=}}</ref>
Habib Elmasry was the secretary of the General Congregation council for three terms, and was known for his strong support of ordination of a monk to be the [[Coptic pope]] and not a metropolitan or a bishop.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}} This issue caused an ongoing dispute in the Coptic Orthodox Church and although [[The Holy Synod of the Coptic Orthodox Church]] had considered in the 1960s the general bishops to be secretaries to the pope in the degree of a [[bishop]], Iris Elmasry in her [[List of Coptic Orthodox Popes of Alexandria]] considered Pope [[Pope Shenouda III of Alexandria|Shenouda III]] (1971–2012), who was a general bishop before, to be the fourth bishop to become a pope after Popes [[Pope John XIX of Alexandria|John XIX]] (1928&ndash;1942), [[Pope Macarius III of Alexandria|Macarius III]] (1942&ndash;1944)and [[Pope Joseph II of Alexandria|Joseph II]] (1946&ndash;1956).<ref>History of the Coptic Church, Iris Habib Elmasry Volume five</ref>
Elmasry received her Bachelor of Arts degree, majoring in education from Maria Grey College, [[University of London]] in 1932.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zoominfo.com/people/El-Masry_Iris_1187715048.aspx |title=Iris El-Masry: ZoomInfo Business People Information |publisher=Zoominfo.com |date= |accessdate=2008-12-05}}</ref>
Between 1952 and 1954, she pursued her research at [[Dropsie College]], [[Philadelphia]], and in 1955, she went to the [[National Gallery, London]], to obtain further materials and documents.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}
In 1954, Pope [[Pope Joseph II of Alexandria|Joseph II]] appointed Elmasry as the female delegate of the Coptic Church to the Second Assembly of the World Council of Churches in Evanston, Illinois, USA.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}
From 1955 to 1985 Elmasry continued to lecture in [[Coptic History]] at both the Seminary in Cairo and Alexandria and at the [[Institute of Coptic Studies]].{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}
She died on July 2, 1994.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}
==Work== Elmasry took interest in the history of the [[Coptic Orthodox Church]] and in 1948 published the first volume of her nine-volumes<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.copticbook.com/Page73.htm|title=www.copticbook.com/Page73.htm<!--INSERT TITLE-->}}</ref> book ''[[Story of the Coptic church]]''.<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite web|url=http://www.wataninet.com/printer.asp?articleid=14312&lang=en|title=Watani}}</ref> The seventh volume of this history is about the era of Pope [[Pope Cyril VI of Alexandria|Cyril VI]] (1959&ndash;1971): the book shows how highly appreciative she was of His Holiness's work.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}
She considered [[Abouna Matta El Meskeen]] the Spiritual Father of the [[Monks]] in St. Macarius' [[Monastery]] in Scetis ([[Egypt]]) as her mentor and always expressed gratitude to him in the introductions to her books and also to father [[Bishoy Kamel]] of Alexandria.<ref name="Copts" />
[[Pope Joseph II of Alexandria|Pope Youssab II]], the 115th Pope (1946–1956), appointed Elmasry in 1954 as his secretary for correspondence with the [[World Council of Churches]]. His successor [[Pope Cyril VI of Alexandria|Pope Kyrillos VI]], the 116th Pope (1959–1971), appointed her in 1966 as Counselor to young Coptic women.<ref name=autogenerated1 />
While Elmasry's Arabic language publications are among the most widely quoted in the historical literature of the Coptic Church, her impressive work as a theologian, politician, psychologist, educator, and philanthropist is not as widely known. An article by Saad (2009)<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Saad|first=Michael|title=Iris Habib el-Masry: A Pioneer of Coptic Feminine Theology|url=https://www.academia.edu/8903323/Iris_Habib_el-Masry_A_Pioneer_of_Coptic_Feminine_Theology|journal=Coptic Church Review|language=en}}</ref> presents an introduction to her contributions to certain areas of politics and theology, while exploring in more detail unique features of her writing that may offer a framework for Coptic feminine theology.
Elmasry's work was very thorough: she made every effort not to omit details that she considered important. As a result, her work is more detailed, and of greater use to both academic and non-academic readers; is valuable for any researcher in [[Coptic history]] and provides a comprehensive approach to the history of Christianity in Egypt and point of view of the [[Coptic Orthodox Church of Alexandria|Coptic Church]] regarding many debatable issue like [[Council of Chalcedon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.orthodoxunity.org/article01.html|title=Orthodox Unity}}</ref>
In the introduction to the first volume of her nine volumes book on the history of the Coptic Church, she mentions a conversation she had with a non-Egyptian about [[Council of Chalcedon]], during which she explained the Coptic view regarding the council.<ref name="Copts" />
She used a lot of sources in her work and mentioned many known scripts in different languages. Her work shows clear affection towards her church, and high esteem for certain people in the church’s history. This may be the reason behind the way she presented the history of Pope [[Pope Cyril III of Alexandria|Cyril III]] in comparison to the way it was presented in Abouna [[Menassa Youhanna]]'s book ''History of the Coptic Church''.<ref>History of the Coptic Church, [[Abouna Menassa Elkomos Youhanna]] 1923</ref>
==Books==
* ''The Blessed Virgin'' (1970) * ''Habib Pascha El Masry'' (1971) * ''The Story of the Copts'', first published in 1975 by the [[Middle East Council of Churches]],<ref name=autogenerated2 /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.antiqbook.nl/boox/rashi/56145.shtml|title=antiqbook}}</ref> * ''Introduction to the Coptic Church'', published in English in 1977 * ''Women in the Church'' (1979) * ''The Pharaonic Influence on Modern Coptic Life'' (1980) * ''Bishop Samuel'' (1983) * ''Father Bishoy Kamel'' (1980)
