{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2014}} {{Use British English|date=October 2014}} {{Infobox person | name = May Holt | birth_name = Elizabeth May Holt | birth_date = {{Birth date|1849|11|14|df=yes}} | birth_place = [[Bury St Edmunds]], [[Suffolk]], England | occupation = [[actress]] and [[playwright]] | years_active = 1857–1910 | spouse = Reginald Fairbairn | children = Ada Fairbairn }}
'''May Holt''' born '''Elizabeth May Holt''' was an English actress, manager and playwright who had a successful career on the stage in England and Australia.”She was claimed with great affection by both the Australian and British press and identified as a peer by her contemporaries and colleagues in both Britain and Australia.” <ref>{{cite book |last=Newey |first=Katherine |editor1-last=Schafer |editor1-first=Elizabeth |editor2-last=Bradley Smith |editor2-first=Susan |title=Playing Australia : Australian Theatre and the International Stage |publisher=Rodopi |date=2003 |pages=93–107 |chapter=Chapter 6: When Is an Australian Playwright not an Australian Playwright? The Case of May Holt |isbn=978-9-042-00817-5}}</ref>
==Early Life and Acting Career== She was born on 14 November 1849 in [[Bury St Edmunds]], [[Suffolk]] the youngest daughter of the [[actor-manager]], [[Clarance Holt]] and she acted in his company from a very early age. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mandmclark.com/index.htm|title=Clark family history|publisher=mandmclark.com|date=|accessdate=2014-11-05}}</ref> In 1857, at the age of 8, she appeared, with the rest of the family, in the melodrama, ''The Children of the Castle'' by [[Edward Fitzball]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://victorian.worc.ac.uk/modx/assets/docs/pdf/Vol35xChildren-.pdf|title=Victorian Plays Project – Children of the Castle|publisher=Victorian.worc.ac.uk|date=|accessdate=2014-11-05}}</ref> May toured with the family throughout Great Britain, Australia and New Zealand and was already receiving top billing in her late teens – playing Ophelia at the age of 18 and starring as Eponine in her father’s adaptation of [[Victor Hugo|Victor Hugo's]] [[Les Miserables]] entitled ''The Barricade'' a year later. She was noted for her singing and dancing in many newspaper reviews and appeared in the Music Halls as well as the theatre. As an example of this versatility: in 1867 she appeared at the [[Theatre Royal, Manchester]] and, after the performance of ''[[Hamlet]]'', starred in the farce ''Easy Shaving'' and sang two popular ballads.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl%2f0000206%2f18670325%2f018|title=May Holt starring at the Theatre Royal Manchester |work=Manchester Courier and Lancashire General Advertiser|date=25 March 1867 |accessdate=5 November 2014}}</ref>
==Career as a Playwright==
In 1880 she married Reginald Fairbairn; she was 30 and he 24.He was the youngest son of Sir [[Thomas Fairbairn]], 2nd Baronet of [[Ardwick]] and the grandson of the famous engineer, Sir [[William Fairbairn]]. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mandmclark.com/index.htm|title=Clark family history|publisher=mandmclark.com|date=|accessdate=2014-11-05}}</ref> After her marriage she continued to appear on the stage but also became an accomplished playwright. Her plays were produced, with considerable success, in both England and Australia.
==Playlist==
Her plays include:- <ref>{{cite book |last=Newey |first=Katherine |editor1-last=Schafer |editor1-first=Elizabeth |editor2-last=Bradley Smith |editor2-first=Susan |title=Playing Australia : Australian Theatre and the International Stage |publisher=Rodopi |date=2003 |pages=93–107 |chapter=Chapter 6: When Is an Australian Playwright not an Australian Playwright? The Case of May Holt |isbn=978-9-042-00817-5}}</ref> * ''Jabez North'' (1881) * ''Sweetheart Goodbye'' (1881) * ''Waiting Consent'' (1881) * ''Men and Women,an entirely new and original drama in seven tableaux'' (1882) * ''False Pride'' (1883) * ''High Art, a new farce'' (1883)
