'''Eduard Nikolaevich Burdzhalov''' (Эдуард Николаевич Бурджалов) (1906–1985) was a Soviet historian.
Burdzhalov graduated from [[Moscow Institute of History, Philosophy, and Literature]] in 1932. He then taught at various Moscow universities, including the [[Moscow State Pedagogical Institute]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://publ.lib.ru/ARCHIVES/B/BURDJALOV_Eduard_Nikolaevich/_Burdjalov_E.N..html | title=Эдуард Николаевич Бурджалов | publisher=Публичная библиотека, | accessdate=September 16, 2012}}</ref> In 1957 he was dismissed as deputy editor of the journal ''[[Questions of History]]'' after he published an article about the [[Bolshevik]]'s confusion following the [[February Revolution]] in 1917.<ref>{{Citation | last = Brooks | first = Jeffrey | title = Review: Rossii kak problema Vsemirnoi istorii: Izbrannye trudy | journal = [[The American Historical Review]] | volume = 107 | issue = 3 | pages = 972–973 | date = June 2002 | doi=10.1086/532638}}</ref> However in 1959 he was appointed professor.
==Publications== * ''Вторая русская революция: Восстание в Петрограде'' (1967) Translated: Raleigh, Donald J. (1987), ''Russia's Second Revolution: The February 1917 Uprising in Petrograd'', Indiana University Press, {{ISBN|978-0-253-20440-0}} * ''Вторая русская революция: Москва. Фронт. Периферия'' (1971).
